I've gotten higher scores, better statistics, and better overall landings without the glide slope. Something tells me that the physics aren't working really well.  I turned up the failures to all, and a super steep glide with heavy flare is too easy to do. Those elevons are not that big. Never flown the real shuttle, but the CG feels odd too.   I"ve also noticed that there is very little in terms of ground-effect. For such a large delta wing, you'd expect more coming out of a steep flare, but there isn't much in the way of float under mild AOA at less than a wingspan of altitude.   Don't get me wrong, its great fun, and super addicting. Just don't think its realistic.

This is a really fantastic flight sim app, which faithfully reproduces the final minutes of a space shuttle flight, either as a final approach or by placing you just before the HAC. As this is the only portion of the flight that is flown by hand in the shuttle, the simulation is extremely realistic.  The graphics are also unbelievable, photorealistic and a beautiful 3D model of the orbiter itself. Inside is a 3D cockpit, complete with HUD that shows everything the real thing has to help you guide the orbiter to a perfect landing. Once you have mastered the basics there are seemingly infinite ways to customise your flight by adding a number of failures, as well as climatic variations like turbulence, wind, gusts and low visibility. With both the Kennedy Space Centre and Edwards Air Force Base available to land at, you can end the flight at both the locations the real thing used to.   Brilliant from start to finish, a real quality app. Buy it now!!!

Works fine on both the Nexus 7 and my HTC One X and looks great. Quite fun taking a shuttle down in a variety of conditions. You can add as much challenge as you want by adding faults, removing assists and changing a bunch of settings. A bit geeky but really different and fun.
